    \begin{block}{MOTIVATION}
In infectious disease epidemiology, the \textbf{agents driving observed outcomes may themselves be unobserved}.
They may be censored by simple scientific practicality or ethicality, but since behavior is involved, their \textbf{missing-ness may deliberate} rather than just incidental.  Consider people's distrust of government during the Ebola outbreak, or the social stigma associated with homosexuality and HIV.

These \textbf{covert individuals may be key to understanding} a system.  \textbf{``Big data'' approaches may help find them}, whether deliberately or incidentally missing, but such tactics are susceptible false positives so we \textbf{need to distinguish between success and luck}.
    \end{block}
    \vspace{.5cm}
    \begin{block}{DETECTING COVERT BEHAVIOR}
We \textbf{do not know the behavior of covert groups} by definition, and we do not generally know who is or isn't hiding in a particular dataset.  However, we can consider the detectability of types hidden groups in some dataset by \textbf{simulating those groups, adding them to the data, and applying the detection procedure}.  That approach assumes groups that participate in whatever activity produces the dataset -- i.e., they do not hide by being non-participants -- which is similar to the background and dominates their activity.  But these groups also have behavior because they are members of this group, and the challenge is to detect them based on that differentiating behavior.
    \end{block}
